description.plain:
With his distinctive flow and catchy ad-libs, Headie One is one of the most prominent rising stars in the UK music scene. Coming from the crime-ridden Broadwater Farm Estate in Tottenham, North London, he began making music in 2010 along with other members of Star Gang, the group that would eventually become OFB, as “Headz.”

In 2014, he released his debut mixtape: Headz or Tails, and soon began to make drill music with his fellow OFB older RV. The duo co-released several popular mixtapes including 2016’s Sticks and Stones and 2017 project Drillers x Trappers. In 2017, he released his second solo tape: The One. On this album was his song “Know Better”, which gained significant notoriety when the media linked it to a series of shootings and stabbings that happened around that time.

From this, Headie continued to release music, culminating in the release of The One Two in 2018. In 2019, Headie had significant commercial success, with songs such as “18HUNNA” with Dave, peaking at number 6 on the UK singles charts, and “I Spy” with Krept & Konan, which peaked at number 18. He also released the long-awaited follow-up project Drillers x Trappers II with RV, featuring tracks with Unknown T, DigDat and Kojo Funds.

Although Headie has generally stuck to drill, he has performed on a variety of different beats. His album Music x Road, released in 2019, saw him rapping over very different styles of music. 2019 also saw him on the Y.OFB song “Once In A While”, the last major release of OFB artist SJ before he went to prison.

In 2020, Headie collaborated with Canadian superstar Drake on “Only You Freestyle” and later with Stormzy and AJ Tracey on their song “Ain’t It Different”. His debut studio album EDNA was released October 2020 to widespread commercial success, debuting at #1. The Deluxe edition of EDNA was released four months later.

True to the song’s title, Headie One appears on a trap-influenced beat rather than a more typical drill sound, sampling melodic elements from the Red Hot Chili Peppers' instrumental track “Pretty Little Ditty”  and UK garage classic “Bump ‘N’ Grind ” by M-Dubs featuring vocalist Lady Saw. This is Headie’s first collaboration with producer Fred again.., who has worked with all three separately, since their EP GANG.

description.plain:
The third track on Headie One’s mixtape “The One” discusses how he and his team, OFB, have won the Golden Boot for ‘scoring’ on his rivals by seriously harming or killing them.

The Golden Boot is an award given to the top goalscorer in the Premier League after a season has finished. After the 2017/18 season, Mohamed Salah (as seen below) was awarded the Golden Boot for scoring 32 times in 36 matches.

This has been a huge hit having amassed around 4.5 million views on YouTube as of September 2019.

description.plain:
Headie One and Aitch join forces on “Parlez-Vous Anglais”—French for “Do you speak English?”. The two British rappers go back and forth and depict their lavish lifestyle throughout eight verses rapped over a laid-back instrumental.

“Parlez-Vous Anglais” is also Headie paying homage to France. Headie raps a few words in French and drops numerous references to French culture, from cities Paris and Saint-Tropez to French luxury fashion brands Yves Saint Laurent, Louis Vuitton, and Chanel.

The song was released as part of Headie One’s debut studio album EDNA alongside a music video starring the two collaborators portraying their expensive tastes in a manor.

description.plain:
“Martins Sofa” is a highly-anticipated single by UK drill heavyweight Headie One. The track samples the instrumental to Flatbush Zombie’s single “Palm Trees” which has become iconic in the UK in it’s own right following late South London MC Cadet’s iconic freestyle “Slut”.

The track is a reflective and sombre ode to Headie’s prominence in rap and his gang-fuelled/drug dealing lifestyle of the past; particularly sofa surfing in the lounge of a local customer named Martin who used to allow Headie to use his sofa in exchange for drugs.

The single has gone viral on social media sites with the running joke being people approaching Headie with: “Headie, when are you dropping Martin’s Sofa?” comes after Headie’s drill-fulled “50s” where he acknowledges Martin’s Sofa, teasing it for his upcoming sophomore studio album:

The fans calling for Martin’s Sofa
It might be the first single from my second–

On the 21st of December, Headie met with the actual Martin who also asked the famed question:

The single has gone viral on social media sites with the running joke being people approaching Headie with: “Headie, when are you dropping Martin’s Sofa?” comes after Headie’s drill-fulled “50s” where he acknowledges Martin’s Sofa, teasing it for his upcoming sophomore studio album:

The fans calling for Martin’s Sofa
It might be the first single from my second–

On the 21st of December, Headie met with the actual Martin who also asked the famed question:
